        content: "Points of Information, or POIs, are one of the most distinctive and exciting features of parliamentary debate. Unlike other debate formats where speakers take turns without interruption, parliamentary debate allows members of the opposing team to stand and offer brief questions or statements during an opponent's speech.\n\nPOIs serve multiple strategic purposes. They can disrupt an opponent's flow, highlight weaknesses in their arguments, introduce your own framing into their speech time, and demonstrate your engagement with the debate. Skillful use of POIs separates competent parliamentary debaters from truly excellent ones.\n\nThis lesson covers both sides of the POI exchange: how to ask effective POIs that advance your position and how to handle incoming POIs with grace, confidence, and strategic intelligence.",
