        content: "Every debater faces a fundamental challenge: you always have more potential arguments than time to present them. A novice debater tries to cram in as many arguments as possible. A master debater carefully selects and prioritizes the arguments that give them the highest probability of winning.\n\nArgument selection is not just about choosing good arguments — it is about choosing the right arguments for this particular round. The best argument in a vacuum might be the wrong argument given your judge, your opponent, the topic wording, and your available evidence.\n\nThis lesson teaches you a systematic approach to argument selection and prioritization. You will learn how to evaluate arguments across multiple dimensions, how to build a coherent case from selected arguments, and how to adapt your selections based on the specific conditions of each round.",
