        content: "Before you can select the best arguments, you need a framework for evaluating them. Strong arguments score well across multiple dimensions.\n\nStrength refers to how well-supported the argument is. Does it have strong evidence? Is the logical chain solid? Can it withstand scrutiny? A strong argument holds up under cross-examination and rebuttal.\n\nRelevance refers to how directly the argument engages with the topic. Arguments that are tangentially related to the resolution may be interesting but fail to address the core question the judge must answer. The most relevant arguments speak directly to the key terms and implications of the resolution.\n\nImpact refers to the magnitude of the argument's conclusion. An argument showing that a policy saves lives has higher impact than one showing it saves money. Impact is what motivates the judge to vote — it answers the question 'So what?'\n\nUniqueness refers to whether the advantage or disadvantage only exists under one side's advocacy. If the benefit you describe would happen regardless of which side wins, the argument lacks uniqueness and does not provide a reason to prefer your position.\n\nAccessibility refers to how easily the judge can understand and evaluate the argument. A brilliant but extremely complex argument may be less effective than a simpler one that the judge can immediately grasp. Know your audience.",
