        content: "One of the biggest fears in impromptu speaking is getting a topic you know little about. Master parliamentary debaters have strategies for building credible arguments even on unfamiliar topics.\n\nFirst, use first-principles reasoning. Even if you do not know specific facts about a topic, you can reason from basic principles. Economics, political science, ethics, and human psychology provide frameworks that apply broadly. If the motion is about a policy you have never heard of, ask yourself: who benefits, who is harmed, what are the incentives, and what are the unintended consequences?\n\nSecond, use analogical reasoning. If you do not know about the specific issue, think of similar situations you do know about. 'While I cannot speak to the specifics of this particular trade agreement, trade liberalization has historically produced these patterns...'\n\nThird, use structural arguments. Some argument types apply across many topics: slippery slope concerns, cost-benefit analysis, rights and freedoms, democratic accountability, and practical implementation challenges. These 'argument templates' can be adapted to almost any motion.\n\nFourth, be honest about uncertainty while remaining confident. You can say 'The evidence suggests' or 'Historical patterns indicate' without claiming perfect knowledge. Judges respect intellectual honesty combined with strong reasoning more than confident bluffing that falls apart under scrutiny.\n\nFifth, leverage your general knowledge. Read widely across topics between tournaments. The more you know about the world, the more raw material you have for impromptu speeches.",
        keyPoints: [
          "Use first-principles reasoning when specific knowledge is lacking",
          "Draw analogies to similar situations you understand better",
          "Adapt structural argument templates to unfamiliar topics",
          "Be honest about uncertainty while maintaining confident reasoning",
        ],
