        title: "Impromptu Delivery Techniques",
        content: "Delivery in impromptu speaking requires techniques beyond what prepared speeches demand. Because you are constructing arguments in real time, you need strategies to maintain fluency and confidence.\n\nUse signposting aggressively. Phrases like 'My first argument is...,' 'My second point addresses...,' and 'Finally, and most importantly...' give you a moment to think while also helping the judge follow your structure. Signposting is your friend in impromptu speaking.\n\nEmbrace strategic pauses. A brief pause before making an important point creates emphasis and gives you a moment to organize your next thought. Silence is far better than filler words like 'um' or 'uh.' Practice being comfortable with two-to-three-second pauses.\n\nUse transitions as thinking time. 'Now, this connects to a broader issue...' or 'Building on this analysis...' are phrases that sound purposeful while giving your brain a few seconds to formulate the next argument.\n\nMaintain eye contact with the judge even when you are thinking. Looking down at notes or up at the ceiling signals uncertainty. Keeping your gaze steady while pausing conveys confidence and thoughtfulness.\n\nSpeak slightly slower than you think you should. Under pressure, most people speed up unconsciously. Deliberately slowing down improves clarity, gives you more thinking time, and projects confidence. A well-paced impromptu speech is always more impressive than a rushed one.",
