        type: "content",
        title: "Common Impromptu Speaking Mistakes",
        content: "Understanding common mistakes helps you avoid them and capitalize when opponents make them.\n\nThe biggest mistake is failing to commit to a position. Some debaters hedge so much in impromptu speaking that the judge cannot tell what they are actually arguing. Take a clear stance, even if you are not entirely sure it is the strongest position. Commitment and conviction are more persuasive than wishy-washy equivocation.\n\nThe second mistake is trying to be too clever. Complex, multi-layered arguments that you might execute brilliantly with hours of preparation often fall apart in impromptu settings. Simple, clear arguments delivered well will beat ambitious arguments delivered poorly every time.\n\nThe third mistake is neglecting your opponent's arguments. In the stress of impromptu speaking, debaters sometimes focus entirely on their own case and forget to engage with what the other side has said. Make sure to allocate time for refutation even if it means running one fewer constructive argument.\n\nThe fourth mistake is poor time management. Running out of time before covering your main points, or finishing two minutes early with nothing left to say, are both damaging. Practice hitting your time targets so that pacing becomes instinctive.\n\nThe fifth mistake is apologizing for lack of preparation. Never say 'I did not have much time to prepare' or 'I am not sure about this, but...' The judge knows you had limited prep time — that is the format. Deliver your arguments with the same confidence you would in a prepared round.",
