        content: "Weighing is a skill that applies across both Public Forum and Parliamentary debate. The five weighing mechanisms — magnitude, probability, timeframe, reversibility, and scope — give you tools to compare competing impacts and explain why yours matter more.\n\nRemember that the best weighing does not just assert a mechanism but explains why that particular mechanism is the most appropriate way to evaluate the round. Saying 'our impact is bigger' is less effective than saying 'magnitude is the right lens here because both sides agree the probability is roughly equal, so the question becomes which impact is larger.'\n\nPrecedent-based arguments complement weighing by providing concrete evidence of what has happened before. When you combine a strong precedent with effective weighing — 'this approach has been tried before, and the results show our impact is both larger in magnitude and more probable' — you create an argument that is extremely difficult to refute.\n\nSimilarly, the argument selection framework ensures you are deploying the right weighing mechanisms with the right arguments. A high-impact argument paired with strong weighing analysis in your closing speech is the recipe for consistent wins at the master level.",
